mission: STP-2: Will launch the U.S. Air Force’s Space Test Program-2 mission with a cluster of military and scientific research satellites.
Crew Dragon Demo 1: Will launch a Crew Dragon spacecraft on an uncrewed test flight to the International Space Station under the auspices of NASA’s commercial crew program.
CST-100 Starliner Orbital Flight Test: Will launch Boeing’s first CST-100 Starliner spacecraft on an unpiloted Orbital Test Flight to the International Space Station.
AEHF 5: Will launch the fifth Advanced Extremely High Frequency (AEHF) satellite.
GPS 3-03: Will launch the U.S. Air Force’s third third-generation navigation satellite for the Global Positioning System.
Arabsat 6A: Will launch the Arabsat 6A communications satellite for Arabsat of Saudi Arabia.
SBIRS GEO 3: U.S. military’s third Space Based Infrared System Geosynchronous satellite
EchoStar 23 communications satellite for EchoStar Corp.
WGS 9 (Wideband Global SATCOM spacecraft)
SES 10 communications satellite
OA-7
NROL-76- A classified spacecraft payload for the U.S. National Reconnaissance Office.
Inmarsat 5 F4-  Communications satellite for Inmarsat of London.
CRS 11- Launching the 13th Dragon spacecraft
BulgariaSat 1- Launching BulgariaSat 1 communications satellite
CRS 12- Launching the 14th Dragon spacecraft
TDRS M- launching the TDRS M communications and data relay satellite for NASA
OTV-5: Will launch the U.S. military’s X-37B, a spaceplane also called the Orbital Test Vehicle
SES 11/EchoStar 105- Will launch the SES-11/EchoStar 105 hybrid communications satellite
NROL-52- Designated AV-075, will launch a classified spacecraft payload for the U.S. National Reconnaissance Office
Koreasat 5A communications satellite for KTsat based in South Korea.

CRS 13: Will launch the 15th Dragon spacecraft mission on its 13th operational cargo delivery flight to the International Space Station. The Falcon 9 rocket’s first stage will return to landing at Landing Zone-1 at Cape Canaveral Air Force Station.

Zuma: Northrop Grumman arranged to launch the Zuma payload with SpaceX on behalf of the U.S. government, but no other details about the mission have been disclosed. Rocket's first stage will make return landing at Landing Zone-1 at Cape Canaveral Air Force Station.
SBIRS Geo Flight 4- Designated AV-076, will launch the U.S. military’s fourth Space Based Infrared System Geosynchronous satellite, or SBIRS GEO 4, for missile early-warning detection.
SES 16/GovSat 1: Will launch the SES 16/GovSat 1 communications satellite for LuxGovSat
Falcon Heavy: A SpaceX Falcon Heavy rocket will launch on its first demonstration flight.
GOES-S: Will launch GOES-S, the second next-generation geostationary weather satellite for NASA and NOAA.
Hispasat 30W-6: Will launch the Hispasat 30W-6 communications satellite
CRS 14: Will launch the 16th Dragon spacecraft mission on its 14th operational cargo delivery flight to the International Space Station.
AFSPC 11: Will launch the Air Force’s EAGLE satellite hosting multiple military experiments.
TESS: Will launch NASA’s Transiting Exoplanet Survey Satellite
Bangabandhu 1: Will launch the Bangabandhu 1 communications satellite for the Bangladesh Telecommunication Regulatory Commission
SES 12: Will launch the SES 12 communications satellite for SES of Luxembourg (Launch is Tentative)
CRS 15: Will launch the 17th Dragon spacecraft mission on its 15th operational cargo delivery flight to the International Space Station.
Telstar 19V: Will launch the Telstar 19V communications satellite for Telesat of Canada.
Merah Putih: Will launch the Merah Putih communications satellite for Telkom Indonesia.
Parker Solar Probe: Will launch NASA’s Parker Solar Probe.
Telstar 18 VANTAGE: Will launch the Telstar 18 VANTAGE communications satellite for Telesat.
AEHF 4: Will launch the fourth Advanced Extremely High Frequency (AEHF) satellite.
Es'hail 2: Will launch the Es’hail 2 communications satellite.
CRS 16: Will launch the 18th Dragon spacecraft mission on its 16th operational cargo delivery flight to the International Space Station.
GPS 3-01: Will launch the U.S. Air Force’s first third-generation navigation satellite for the Global Positioning System.
WGS 10: Will launch the 10th Wideband Global SATCOM spacecraft, formerly known as the Wideband Gapfiller Satellite.
CRS 17: Will launch the 19th Dragon spacecraft mission on its 17th operational cargo delivery flight to the International Space Station.
GPS 3-02: Will launch the U.S. Air Force’s second third-generation navigation satellite for the Global Positioning System.
CRS 18: Will launch the 20th Dragon spacecraft mission on its 18th operational cargo delivery flight to the International Space Station.
